summary: AJAX-JUVENTUS: RONALDO'S DETACHING ACCELERATION ON HIS GOAL
title: AJAX-JUVENTUS: RONALDO'S DETACHING ACCELERATION ON HIS GOAL
body:
Cristiano Ronaldo opened the scoring in the quarter-final first leg of the UEFA Champions League between Ajax Amsterdam and Juventus (1-1) on Wednesday by initiating the action he concluded a few seconds later. a beautiful head.



Juventus can still thank Cristiano Ronaldo after his quarter-final first leg of the Champions League on Wednesday at the field of Ajax Amsterdam (1-1). Already the author of a hat-trick in the round of 16 against Atlético de Madrid (3-0), the Portuguese striker opened the scoring for the Old Lady on an action he initiated himself. Everything started with a left-sided touch and a first stint with Uruguayan midfielder Rodrigo Bentancur. The latter served Cristiano Ronaldo in the heart of the game.

At 45 meters from the goal and tight little by Daley Blind, who seems to be preparing for a one-on-one duel, Ronaldo turns to the right for his compatriot Joao Cancelo. The side benefits from a call from his teammate Federico Bernardeschi to advance. Meanwhile, Ronaldo embarked on a 40-meter sprint that completely surprised the Dutch defense (Blind went to Cancelo’s laundry, De Jong did not follow CR7). But not Cancelo.

Five seconds that change everything

The latter perfectly followed the race of his teammate that he served as a perfect ball at the penalty spot. Completely lonely, the former Real Madrid player then punctuated his 5 seconds race with a diving head too powerful for André Onana to push back. A goal that was created almost alone Ronaldo. And a stroke of genius that allowed the men of Massimiliano Allegri to deceive the vigilance of the opposing defense, impregnable the rest of the game.

Ronaldo was recovering from a thigh injury

Malménée, the Juve finally left the Johan Cruyff Arena in favorable wagering thanks to this new realization of Ronaldo which, remember it, had not played for two weeks in order to cure a wound on the thigh. His very intense sprint proved that he was very well recovered.

summary: MANCHESTER UNITED: FOR LUKAKU, "BARCELONA IS ANOTHER TEAM" AS PSG
title: MANCHESTER UNITED: FOR LUKAKU, "BARCELONA IS ANOTHER TEAM" AS PSG
body:
Beaten Wednesday by Barça (1-0) in the quarter-final first leg of the Champions League, Manchester United will be looking in a week of a new comeback. For Romelu Lukaku, however, the task will be more difficult than against the PSG.

They dream of the same scenario. Defeated by Barça (1-0) in the quarterfinal first leg of the Champions League, Paul Pogba and his teammates hope to redo the coup PSG. Beaten 2-0 at Old Trafford by the Parisians, Manchester United earned their qualification with a 3-1 win at Parc des Princes. “The performance in Paris gives us the hope that we can do it, but going to Camp Nou is a big challenge, it would be a bigger feat,” said Ole Gunnar Solskjaer, who believes in the chances of his team to perform a feat next Tuesday in the lair of Barça (21h, to be followed exclusively on RMC Sport). Romelu Lukaku also wants to remain optimistic, even if he expects another challenge than against the PSG.

“It’s going to be a lot harder”

“Barcelona is another team, with all the respect for PSG, we had a lot of luck with us there that night, but against Barcelona, ​​it’s going to be a lot more difficult,” he said. the Belgian striker, who believes that Manchester United “could have done better” Wednesday night.

“There was space to play, but it’s Barcelona, ​​we know they have quality and they can make a difference at any time.” There is a bit of frustration, but I think that we have the qualities in our team to make the difference there, but we have to be focused throughout the match, “said Lukaku, who had contributed greatly to the quarterback Red Devils qualifying by scoring twice in the Park.

title: Sports Flash

summary: No one feels Leicester are too good to go down – Tigers have lost their way
title: No one feels Leicester are too good to go down – Tigers have lost their way
body:
When Leicester sacked Dean Richards at the beginning of 2004, the reaction was seismic. Not only had 23 years at the club as a player and the director of rugby been abruptly terminated but the Tigers had won four Premiership titles and two European Cups under the former England No 8 who paid for his job after two league finishes the club would now happily take, sixth and fifth.

Leicester sacking the man at the top now creates more of a reaction for its timing than its occurrence, Matt O’Connor after one match this season, Richard Cockerill halfway through the 2016-17 campaign. If the decision to remove Richards were vindicated with the next nine seasons culminating in Premiership finals at Twickenham, five of which were won, recent dismissals have tended to accelerate decline rather than halt it.

Related: The Breakdown | Alex Goode and the mystery of players stuck outside international rugby

Leicester lost 14 matches during Richards’s four title years from 1998-99, a figure that on form they will at least match this season having been beaten 12 times in the Premiership with four rounds to go. They are at Newcastle on Friday night, their first eight-pointer in the Premiership.

A year ago, the sides met with something at stake at Welford Road. It was a place in the top four, rather than the Championship, a position that had been Leicester’s since the season after they sacked Richards. He returned to Welford Road with Newcastle and they duly won there in the league for the first time since 1997 to make the play-offs.

Leicester have never failed to qualify for the European Cup but that is less of a concern this week than their Premiership status. No one is saying they are too good to go down and not just because their recent record suggests the reverse. A club that defined itself, easily identifiable in the way it played, is lost.

It remains the best supported in the Premiership but it no longer has the highest turnover having fallen behind Wasps, Harlequins and Exeter, with Bath catching up. “When I left, we had never been out of the top four and had won the Premiership three times,” said Cockerill last month. “More than two years later, they are in the bottom three and have had three head coaches since I left. The people who are making the decisions are going to have to take the responsibility. There is too much self-interest in the club.”

Cockerill’s departure summed up the confused state of Leicester. Like Richards, he had been moulded by the club, part of what it stood for, so when Aaron Mauger was brought into his coaching team from above, the former New Zealand centre who had finished his playing career at Welford Road, there was a clash of styles. They became more adventurous but also easier to score against. Confusion replaced certainty.

Mauger did not last much longer than Cockerill and that summer Leicester traded their second-row Ed Slater for the Gloucester and England wing Jonny May. If it summed up the shift in emphasis to greater potency behind rather than at forward, it created an imbalance which has been evident this season.

Richard Cockerill’s departure halfway through the 2016-17 campaign summed up the confused state of Leicester. Photograph: Andrew Boyers/Reuters

The Leicester chief executive, Simon Cohen, said in his programme notes last weekend that when he looks at the club’s squad, “it looks as good as any in the Premiership”. His words did not carry much resonance after a match that Exeter won 52-20, the most points Leicester had conceded in the tournament.

A glance at the two benches challenged his contention. Exeter had an all-international front row, as Leicester did in the year they last won the title when Dan Cole and Martin Castrogiovanni tighthead prop, with Marcos Ayerza and Logovi’i Mulipola the options on the other side; sandwiched between them was Tom Youngs or George Chuter.

Leicester’s replacement front row against Exeter had made 19 starts for the club between them. Injuries were a factor behind the inexperience but Leicester lack the depth of old. When they last won the Premiership in 2013, Castrogiovanni, Slater, Steve Mafi and George Ford were on the bench.

The starting lineup included Vereniki Goneva, Toby Flood and Mulipola, who all started for Newcastle at Saracens last weekend. Three forwards that season, Geoff Parling, Thomas Waldrom and Julian Salvi, were to leave for Exeter. Leicester no longer seem to sign forwards of international quality, despite two marquee players being allowed on top of the salary cap.

So while they have a back division as threatening as most, the failure to invest in the supply line and produce a Leicester-style pack has left the backs having to do more defending than attacking. The result is the leakiest defence in the Premiership and from being a side who would have been recognisable without shirts on, it is difficult to discern now what the Tigers stand for.

“What are Leicester?” asked Cockerill, answering his own question with: “They are neither one thing nor the other.” And so England’s most successful club in terms of trophies won heads for Newcastle, a well-trodden route made unfamiliar by the plight it finds itself in.

The three other relegation contenders are used to battling at the wrong end of the table. Leicester’s lineup against Exeter contained six of the current England squad: Newcastle, Worcester and Bristol have two between them. It is about the mongrel within, and while the outcome on Friday will not determine Leicester’s fate, it is taking the shock of failure to jolt the club into facing reality. As Manchester United found in 1974, the bigger the club, the harder the fall.

• This is an extract from our weekly rugby union email, the Breakdown. To subscribe just visit this page and follow the instructions.

“What are Leicester?” asked Cockerill, answering his own question with: “They are neither one thing nor the other.” And so England’s most successful club in terms of trophies won heads for Newcastle, a well-trodden route made unfamiliar by the plight it finds itself in.

Leicester’s lineup against Exeter contained six of the current England squad: Newcastle, Worcester and Bristol have two between them. As Manchester United found in 1974, the bigger the club, the harder the fall.

Not only had 23 years at the club as a player and the director of rugby been abruptly terminated but the Tigers had won four Premiership titles and two European Cups under the former England No 8 who paid for his job after two league finishes the club would now happily take, sixth and fifth.

Leicester sacking the man at the top now creates more of a reaction for its timing than its occurrence, Matt O’Connor after one match this season, Richard Cockerill halfway through the 2016-17 campaign. If the decision to remove Richards were vindicated with the next nine seasons culminating in Premiership finals at Twickenham, five of which were won, recent dismissals have tended to accelerate decline rather than halt it.

Related: The Breakdown | Alex Goode and the mystery of players stuck outside international rugby

A year ago, the sides met with something at stake at Welford Road. It was a place in the top four, rather than the Championship, a position that had been Leicester’s since the season after they sacked Richards. He returned to Welford Road with Newcastle and they duly won there in the league for the first time since 1997 to make the play-offs.

No one is saying they are too good to go down and not just because their recent record suggests the reverse. A club that defined itself, easily identifiable in the way it played, is lost.

The people who are making the decisions are going to have to take the responsibility. There is too much self-interest in the club.”

Cockerill’s departure summed up the confused state of Leicester. Like Richards, he had been moulded by the club, part of what it stood for, so when Aaron Mauger was brought into his coaching team from above, the former New Zealand centre who had finished his playing career at Welford Road, there was a clash of styles.
